GraphicsDevice and GraphicsDeviceManager

Relevant source files
  • MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/DisplayMode.cs
  • MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/DisplayModeCollection.cs
  • MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsAdapter.cs
  • MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsCapabilities.cs

  • MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/Viewport.cs
  • MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs
  • MonoGame.Framework/IGraphicsDeviceManager.cs

The GraphicsDevice and GraphicsDeviceManager are core components of MonoGame's graphics system that manage the connection between your game and the graphics hardware. They provide mechanisms for configuring the display, initializing graphics resources, and performing rendering operations.

For information about specific rendering techniques like sprite rendering, see SpriteBatch and 2D Rendering. For information about graphics states, see Graphics States.

Overview

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsDevice.cs15-46 MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs11-14

Responsibilities

ComponentPrimary Responsibilities
GraphicsDeviceManagerCreates and manages the GraphicsDevice, handles device configuration, manages presentation parameters, controls fullscreen/windowed mode, handles device creation and reset, configures display settings
GraphicsDevicePerforms primitive-based rendering, creates and manages graphics resources, maintains graphics states, handles viewports, provides access to adapter capabilities

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsDevice.cs15-18 MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs11-13

GraphicsDeviceManager

Purpose

The GraphicsDeviceManager is responsible for:

  1. Creating and initializing the GraphicsDevice
  2. Configuring display settings (resolution, fullscreen, etc.)
  3. Managing the lifecycle of the GraphicsDevice
  4. Coordinating the beginning and end of drawing operations
  5. Presenting the rendered content to the screen

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs11-14

Key Properties

The GraphicsDeviceManager provides several properties for configuring the graphics device:

PropertyDescriptionDefault Value
PreferredBackBufferWidthDesired width of the back bufferWindow client width
PreferredBackBufferHeightDesired height of the back bufferWindow client height
PreferredBackBufferFormatDesired color format of the back bufferSurfaceFormat.Color
PreferredDepthStencilFormatDesired depth formatDepthFormat.Depth24
SynchronizeWithVerticalRetraceWhether to use vsynctrue
IsFullScreenWhether to render in fullscreenfalse
GraphicsProfileFeature level to use (Reach or HiDef)GraphicsProfile.Reach
PreferMultiSamplingWhether to use multisampling (anti-aliasing)false
PreferHalfPixelOffsetWhether to use DirectX 9 style pixel addressingfalse

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs19-31 MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs421-645

Applying Changes

Changes to the GraphicsDeviceManager properties are not applied immediately. To apply changes, you must call ApplyChanges():

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs341-373

GraphicsDevice

Purpose

The GraphicsDevice is the core rendering component that:

  1. Performs primitive-based rendering operations
  2. Creates and manages graphics resources (textures, buffers, etc.)
  3. Controls graphics state (blend states, rasterizer states, etc.)
  4. Provides information about graphics capabilities
  5. Manages the viewport and render targets

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsDevice.cs15-18

Graphics Configuration

Graphics Adapter

The GraphicsAdapter represents a physical display adapter (graphics card) and provides information about:

  1. Available display modes (resolutions and formats)
  2. Current display mode
  3. Adapter capabilities

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsAdapter.cs10-11 MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsAdapter.cs46-55

Graphics Capabilities

The GraphicsCapabilities class exposes information about what the current graphics device supports:

CategoryCapabilities
Texture SupportNon-power-of-two textures, texture arrays, texture filter anisotropy, max texture anisotropy, etc.
Format SupportFloating point textures, half-float textures, DXT1/3/5 compression, PVRTC compression, etc.
Feature SupportDepth formats, instancing, separate blend states, vertex textures, etc.

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsCapabilities.cs10-15 MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsCapabilities.cs25-127

Device Events

Both GraphicsDevice and GraphicsDeviceManager expose events for monitoring the device lifecycle:

EventDescription
DeviceCreatedRaised when a GraphicsDevice is created
DeviceDisposingRaised when a GraphicsDevice is being disposed
DeviceResettingRaised when a GraphicsDevice is about to be reset
DeviceResetRaised after a GraphicsDevice has been reset
ResourceCreatedRaised when a graphics resource is created
ResourceDestroyedRaised when a graphics resource is destroyed

Fullscreen Management

The GraphicsDeviceManager provides methods for controlling fullscreen mode:

  1. Set IsFullScreen property
  2. Call ApplyChanges()
  3. Or use ToggleFullScreen() to switch between windowed and fullscreen modes

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs401-460

Pixel Addressing and Half-Pixel Offset

MonoGame can use either:

  1. Modern pixel addressing (default): Where pixel centers are at integer coordinates
  2. DirectX 9 style pixel addressing (PreferHalfPixelOffset = true): Where pixel centers are at half-integer coordinates

This affects texture sampling and rendering coordinates and primarily exists for XNA compatibility.

Sources: MonoGame.Framework/GraphicsDeviceManager.cs478-501 MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsDevice.cs21-34

Common Usage Patterns

Basic Setup

public Game1() : base()
{
    graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager(this);
    Content.RootDirectory = "Content";
    
    // Configure graphics
    graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1280;
    graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 720;
    graphics.PreferMultiSampling = true;
    graphics.SynchronizeWithVerticalRetrace = true;
    graphics.ApplyChanges();
}

Changing Resolution at Runtime

public void ChangeResolution(int width, int height)
{
    graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = width;
    graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = height;
    graphics.ApplyChanges();
}

Detecting Graphics Capabilities

protected override void Initialize()
{
    base.Initialize();
    
    var capabilities = GraphicsDevice.GraphicsCapabilities;
    bool supportsFloatTextures = capabilities.SupportsFloatTextures;
    bool supportsNonPowerOfTwo = capabilities.SupportsNonPowerOfTwo;
    
    // Use this information to adapt your rendering approach
}
